\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces The Lock-In Extraction pipeline. A source document is segmented into $N$ spans; a Hadamard design assigns binary carriers, producing $K$ variant documents via negation-based modulation. All variants are re-extracted under a frozen predicate schema, yielding a presence matrix $P \in \{0,1\}^{K \times A}$. The phi coefficient between each atom's presence vector and each carrier separates causally grounded atoms (high $|\phi |$) from prior-driven hallucinations (near-zero $|\phi |$ across all carriers). Calibrated survivors are loaded into the Prolog knowledge base.}}{3}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:pipeline}{{1}{3}{The Lock-In Extraction pipeline. A source document is segmented into $N$ spans; a Hadamard design assigns binary carriers, producing $K$ variant documents via negation-based modulation. All variants are re-extracted under a frozen predicate schema, yielding a presence matrix $P \in \{0,1\}^{K \times A}$. The phi coefficient between each atom's presence vector and each carrier separates causally grounded atoms (high $|\phi |$) from prior-driven hallucinations (near-zero $|\phi |$ across all carriers). Calibrated survivors are loaded into the Prolog knowledge base}{figure.1}{}}
